data.content:
Here's the modern, type-safe version using **ValueTuple-based `DynamicData`** (MSTest 3.7+):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)>` — compile-time type checking, no runtime casts
- `["valid@email.com", true]` → `("valid@email.com", true)` — tuple syntax instead of array syntax

The test method signature stays the same. MSTest destructures the tuple into the method parameters automatically.

If you need custom display names per case, wrap with `TestDataRow<T>`:

```csharp
public static IEnumerable<TestDataRow<(string input, bool expected)>> TestData =>
[
    new(("valid@email.com", true)) { DisplayName = "Valid email" },
    new(("invalid", false))        { DisplayName = "Missing @" },
    new(("", false))               { DisplayName = "Empty string" },
];
```

Requires **MSTest 3.7+** (via `MSTest` package or `MSTest.Sdk`).
